Introduction to Computer Vision: Plant Seedlings Classification¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term. The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can actually benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor, could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human inolvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

Objective¶

The aim of this project is to Build a Convolutional Neural Netowrk to classify plant seedlings into their respective categories.

Data Dictionary¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with the University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species.

  • The dataset can be download from Olympus.

  • The data file names are:

    • images.npy
    • Labels.csv

  • Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to the images.npy file and the labels are also put into Labels.csv, so that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without having to worry about the high data volume.

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

List of Species

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common Wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

def plot_images(images,labels):
  num_classes=10                                                                  # Number of Classes
  categories=np.unique(labels)
  keys=dict(labels['Label'])                                                      # Obtaing the unique classes from y_train
  rows = 3                                                                        # Defining number of rows=3
  cols = 4                                                                        # Defining number of columns=4
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))                                               # Defining the figure size to 10x8
  for i in range(cols):
      for j in range(rows):
          random_index = np.random.randint(0, len(labels))                        # Generating random indices from the data and plotting the images
          ax = fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, i * rows + j + 1)                      # Adding subplots with 3 rows and 4 columns
          ax.imshow(images[random_index, :])                                      # Plotting the image
          ax.set_title(keys[random_index])
  plt.show()

Resize the images¶

As the size of the images is large, it may be computationally expensive to train on these larger images; therefore, it is preferable to reduce the image size from 128 to 64.

In [14]:
images_decreased=[]
height = 64
width = 64
dimensions = (width, height)
for i in range(len(images)):
  images_decreased.append( cv2.resize(images[i], dimensions, interpolation=cv2.INTER_LINEAR))

Data Preparation for Modeling¶

  • Before you proceed to build a model, you need to split the data into train, test, and validation to be able to evaluate the model that you build on the train data
  • You'll have to encode categorical features and scale the pixel values.
  • You will build a model using the train data and then check its performance

Split the dataset

  • As we have less images in our dataset, we will only use 10% of our data for testing, 10% of our data for validation and 80% of our data for training.
  • We are using the train_test_split() function from scikit-learn. Here, we split the dataset into three parts, train,test and validation.

Data Normalization¶

Since the image pixel values range from 0-255, our method of normalization here will be scaling - we shall divide all the pixel values by 255 to standardize the images to have values between 0-1.

Model Building¶

Let's define a function to output different metrics (including recall) on the train, validation and test set.

In [20]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of CNN model
def model_performance(model, predictors, target,modeldesc=None):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check CNN model performance

    model: CNN
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred_probs = model.predict(predictors) # Get predicted probabilities
    pred = np.argmax(pred_probs, axis=1)  # Get predicted classes (0-11)

    # Convert target to multiclass format if it's in multilabel-indicator format
    if target.ndim == 2 and target.shape[1] > 1:  # Check if multilabel-indicator
        target = np.argmax(target, axis=1)  # Convert to multiclass format

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute weighted Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute weighted Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute weighted F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics along with model description
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Model": modeldesc,
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Let's create a CNN model sequentially, where we will be adding the layers one after another.

First, we need to clear the previous model's history from the session even if a single model can run multiple times on the same data.

In Keras, we need a special command to clear the model's history, otherwise the previous model history remains in the backend.

Also, let's fix the seed again after clearing the backend.

Let's set the seed for random number generators in Numpy, the Random library in Python, and in TensorFlow to be able to reproduce the same results every time we run the code.

Now, let's build a CNN Model with the following 2 main parts -

  1. The Feature Extraction layers which are comprised of convolutional and pooling layers.
  2. The Fully Connected classification layers for prediction.

In [24]:
# Intializing a sequential model
model = Sequential()

# Adding first conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension of images
model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))

# Adding max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 100 neurons
model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))
# Adding the output layer with 12 neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem
model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Using SGD Optimizer
# opt = SGD(learning_rate=0.01, momentum=0.9)
opt=Adam()
# Compile model
model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Generating the summary of the model
model.summary()

Observations:

  • Validation Accuracy Above Training: We can observe from the plot that the validation accuracy curve is consistently above the training accuracy curve throughout the training process.
  • General Trend of Increasing Accuracy: Both curves show a general trend of increasing accuracy.
  • Final Validation Accuracy: The model achieves a final validation accuracy of 0.5748 at the last epoch, while the corresponding training accuracy is 0.4801.
  • Overfitting Indication: The training accuracy (0.655056) being higher than the validation accuracy (0.574766) suggests some degree of overfitting.
  • Low Overall Performance: The model's overall performance is relatively low, suggesting that it may not be effectively capturing the underlying patterns in the data.

Plotting the Confusion Matrix¶

  • The Confusion matrix is also defined as an inbuilt function in the TensorFlow module, so we can use that for evaluating the classification model.
  • The Confusion matrix expects categorical data as input. However, y_test_encoded is an encoded value, whereas y_pred has probabilities. So,we must retrieve the categorical values from the encoded values.
  • We will use the argmax() function to obtain the maximum value over each category on both y_test_encoded and y_pred and obtain their respective classes.
In [35]:
# Obtaining the categorical values from y_test_encoded and y_pred
y_pred_arg=np.argmax(y_pred,axis=1)
y_test_arg=np.argmax(y_test_encoded,axis=1)

# Plotting the Confusion Matrix using confusion matrix() function which is also predefined tensorflow module
confusion_matrix = tf.math.confusion_matrix(y_test_arg,y_pred_arg)
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(
    confusion_matrix,
    annot=True,
    linewidths=.4,
    fmt="d",
    square=True,
    ax=ax
)
plt.show()

Observations

  • Overall Misclassification: We observe significant misclassification across several classes.
  • Well-Classified Classes: Classes 1, 3, 6, 8, and 10 are relatively well classified.
  • Complete Misclassification: Classes 0, 4, and 7 are completely misclassified.
  • Frequent Misclassification: Classes 2, 9, and 11 are frequently misclassified, indicating difficulty in distinguishing them.
  • Partial Classification Success: Class 5 shows partial success in learning the features, exhibiting moderate classification.

Model Performance Improvement¶

Reducing the Learning Rate:

Hint: Use ReduceLRonPlateau() function that will be used to decrease the learning rate by some factor, if the loss is not decreasing for some time. This may start decreasing the loss at a smaller learning rate. There is a possibility that the loss may still not decrease. This may lead to executing the learning rate reduction again in an attempt to achieve a lower loss.

In [36]:
# Create a ReduceLROnPlateau callback
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(
    monitor='val_accuracy',   # Metric to monitor
    factor=0.2,               # Reduce the learning rate by 80%
    patience=3,               # Number of epochs with no improvement after which learning rate will be reduced
    min_lr=1e-5,              # Minimum learning rate
    verbose=1
)

# Intializing a sequential model
model_da = Sequential()

# Adding first conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension images
model_da.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))

# Adding max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model_da.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))
# model.add(BatchNormalization())
model_da.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model_da.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))
model_da.add(BatchNormalization())
# flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model_da.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 100 neurons
model_da.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model_da.add(Dropout(0.3))
# Adding the output layer with 12 neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem
model_da.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Using SGD Optimizer
# opt = SGD(learning_rate=0.01, momentum=0.9)
opt=Adam()
# Compile model
model_da.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Generating the summary of the model
model_da.summary()

Conclusion

Based on the comparative analysis of the base CNN model and the CNN model with data augmentation, the CNN with Data Augmentation is the best model for Plant Seedlings Classification. This conclusion is supported by the following observations:

  • Improved Overall Accuracy: The CNN with Data Augmentation achieved a higher test accuracy of 58.74%, compared to the base CNN model's 56%. This indicates an improvement in the model's ability to generalize to unseen data.
  • Reduced Overfitting: The data augmentation model demonstrates a smaller gap between training and validation accuracy, suggesting reduced overfitting and better generalization.
  • Enhanced Precision and Recall: The CNN with data augmentation model exhibits improved precision and recall scores for validation and test data, indicating a better balance in correctly classifying both positive and negative instances.

Though the base CNN model has a slightly higher training accuracy (0.655056 vs. 0.635560), this advantage is outweighed by its poorer generalization, making the CNN with Data Augmentation the clear winner.

plt.show()

print('True Label', enc.inverse_transform(y_test_encoded)[36])                                              # using inverse_transform() to get the output label from the output vector

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights

  • Dataset Imbalance Affects Performance: Imbalanced data (e.g., ~200 samples for Common Wheat, Maize vs. 600+ for Loose Silky-bent) leads to complete misclassification of underrepresented classes.
  • Data Augmentation Improves Generalization: CNN with Data Augmentation achieves better test accuracy (58.74% vs. 56.00%) and reduces overfitting (training-to-validation gap: 0.035093 vs. 0.080290).
  • Suboptimal Model Performance: Test accuracy of 58.74% (Final CNN Model with data augmentation) is too low for practical use; the final model may not capture complex plant features.
  • Feature Overlap Problem: Species with similar leaf shape, color, or growth patterns are frequently misclassified.

Business Recommendations

  • Balance the Dataset: Collect more images for underrepresented classes (e.g., Common Wheat, Maize).
  • Enhance Data Augmentation: Apply advanced augmentation (e.g., rotation, color jittering) and feature engineering (e.g., edge detection for leaf shape) to better distinguish similar species.
  • Use Advanced Models: Experiment with advanced models and leverage transfer learning to improve accuracy for complex plant image classification.
  • Prioritize High-Impact Classes: Focus on accurate classification of weeds (e.g., Black-grass, Cleavers) and crops (e.g., Common Wheat).
  • Implement Two-Stage Classification: Group similar classes (e.g., grass-like weeds) and use a secondary classifier to distinguish them, addressing feature overlap issues.
  • Deploy in a User-Friendly App: Integrate the classifier into a mobile/web app with real-time identification, confidence scores, and weed/crop management recommendations for farmers.
  • Enable Continuous Improvement: Create a feedback loop for farmers to report misclassifications, retrain the model with new data, and monitor performance in real-world conditions.
